00:33:38.515 --> 00:33:39.220
[END PLAYBACK]

00:33:39.220 --> 00:33:41.500
ART WOLFE: So that's enough
of a commercial there.

00:33:41.500 --> 00:33:45.690
But people that go with us
have a great amount of time.

00:33:45.690 --> 00:33:47.250
We set up good shots.

00:33:47.250 --> 00:33:48.260
We know the area.

00:33:48.260 --> 00:33:51.300
So if you're inclined,
just talk to me afterwards.

00:33:51.300 --> 00:33:55.490
Otherwise I'm very happy to
talk to you about anything

00:33:55.490 --> 00:33:58.555
you might want to
ask a question about.

00:33:58.555 --> 00:34:00.430
DAVID: Please come up
here and ask questions.

00:34:00.430 --> 00:34:02.010
ART WOLFE: Don't be shy.

00:34:02.010 --> 00:34:03.990
I should acknowledge
Rob Shepard.

00:34:03.990 --> 00:34:07.380
He has worked with us
for a number of years.

00:34:07.380 --> 00:34:11.060
He was the editor on this book.

00:34:11.060 --> 00:34:12.949
He used to be the
managing editor

00:34:12.949 --> 00:34:14.340
for "Outdoor Photographer."

00:34:14.340 --> 00:34:16.190
So our history goes
back a long time.

00:34:16.190 --> 00:34:19.370
I think he and Deirdre
Skillman in my office

00:34:19.370 --> 00:34:22.650
did a great book on
putting this book together.

00:34:22.650 --> 00:34:25.639
And it's the first time I
can look back with clarity

00:34:25.639 --> 00:34:28.080
and know when it happened.

00:34:28.080 --> 00:34:30.650
So for old people like
me it's really important.

00:34:30.650 --> 00:34:32.100
Yes?

00:34:32.100 --> 00:34:34.489
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned
that technology has actually

00:34:34.489 --> 00:34:37.030
changed landscape
photography quite a bit.

00:34:37.030 --> 00:34:39.870
So I wonder, do you always
go back to your trusty SLR

00:34:39.870 --> 00:34:42.429
or do you explore other
things like smartphones?

00:34:42.429 --> 00:34:44.659
ART WOLFE: You
know, the answer is

00:34:44.659 --> 00:34:46.770
I photograph with everything.

00:34:46.770 --> 00:34:51.510
I have a smartphone that allows
me to photograph in the moment.

00:34:51.510 --> 00:34:55.500
And many of those photos
populate my lectures.

00:34:55.500 --> 00:34:57.280
So yeah, I'm not
a snob about it.

00:34:57.280 --> 00:34:59.980
If you take a workshop
from me or travel with me,

00:34:59.980 --> 00:35:02.780
I don't engage in
whether one camera

00:35:02.780 --> 00:35:04.430
is better than the other.

00:35:04.430 --> 00:35:06.087
It's all about what
the subject is.

00:35:06.087 --> 00:35:07.670
And the camera you've
got in your hand

00:35:07.670 --> 00:35:09.330
is the one you should be using.

00:35:09.330 --> 00:35:12.040
So, yeah, all those cameras.

00:35:12.040 --> 00:35:16.370
I have high end cameras,
but I also have the phones.

00:35:16.370 --> 00:35:16.909
Yeah?

00:35:16.909 --> 00:35:18.450
AUDIENCE: What are
some tips that you

00:35:18.450 --> 00:35:21.470
could give to people who
do work the nine to five

00:35:21.470 --> 00:35:23.980
that still want to be good
photographers, especially up

00:35:23.980 --> 00:35:26.390
here in the Pacific
Northwest, just to encourage

00:35:26.390 --> 00:35:28.120
them to get out and shoot?

00:35:28.120 --> 00:35:30.920
ART WOLFE: Yeah, you know,
you live in the Northwest,

00:35:30.920 --> 00:35:34.070
and we live, I believe, in
the best part of the country

00:35:34.070 --> 00:35:36.590
because an hour and a
half drive from Seattle,

00:35:36.590 --> 00:35:38.740
you can be in the
northern steppe forest,

00:35:38.740 --> 00:35:41.420
out on the coast,
in the mountains,

00:35:41.420 --> 00:35:43.010
in the old growth
forest-- I mean,

00:35:43.010 --> 00:35:46.787
there's so much at a
really quick access point.

00:35:46.787 --> 00:35:48.370
There's a lot of
lectures being given.

00:35:48.370 --> 00:35:49.930
I teach a lot of workshops.

00:35:49.930 --> 00:35:53.730
I think just getting out there
and discovering the place

00:35:53.730 --> 00:35:55.550
that you-- I would
presume many of you

00:35:55.550 --> 00:35:58.090
have moved here from
out of the state.

00:35:58.090 --> 00:36:01.870
There's an amazing array
of subjects to shoot.

00:36:01.870 --> 00:36:04.820
And I think it's just
great for the soul.

00:36:04.820 --> 00:36:07.240
I mean, I love to work
seven days a week.

00:36:07.240 --> 00:36:08.860
I never take a vacation.

00:36:08.860 --> 00:36:12.970
For me, taking pictures
actually delivers energy to me.

00:36:12.970 --> 00:36:14.610
So I love that fact.

00:36:14.610 --> 00:36:17.070
Creative types, people
that are creative,

00:36:17.070 --> 00:36:20.440
whether it's cooking or
dance or poetry or writing,

00:36:20.440 --> 00:36:24.330
photography, they live longer
lives than the average person

00:36:24.330 --> 00:36:25.960
because the word is passion.

00:36:25.960 --> 00:36:30.535
If you have that passion,
in anything, do it to help.

00:36:30.535 --> 00:36:32.590
I sound like an
evangelist on the stage,

00:36:32.590 --> 00:36:34.160
but it's really true.

00:36:34.160 --> 00:36:36.020
I study a lot of art history.

00:36:36.020 --> 00:36:39.150
And the famous artists, if
they didn't drink themselves

00:36:39.150 --> 00:36:42.550
to death, they lived long lives.

00:36:42.550 --> 00:36:43.965
So yes, anyway?

00:36:47.130 --> 00:36:49.690
AUDIENCE: So what do you
think about drone photography?

00:36:49.690 --> 00:36:51.190
ART WOLFE: I love
drone photography.

00:36:51.190 --> 00:36:55.740
I think drone photography is
offering us points of view

00:36:55.740 --> 00:36:58.080
that you would
not otherwise see.

00:36:58.080 --> 00:37:00.520
So you know, it's like
one of those things.

00:37:00.520 --> 00:37:02.649
There's a love-hate
relationship, right?

00:37:02.649 --> 00:37:04.940
People don't like the sound
of a drone over their head,

00:37:04.940 --> 00:37:07.090
but they love looking
at the pictures.

00:37:07.090 --> 00:37:10.150
We all saw the BBC's
"Planet Earth,"

00:37:10.150 --> 00:37:12.270
and many of the photos
in "Planet Earth"

00:37:12.270 --> 00:37:13.890
were shot from drones.

00:37:13.890 --> 00:37:17.050
And the same people
that love that

00:37:17.050 --> 00:37:19.790
are the first ones that would
complain if they hear a drone.

00:37:19.790 --> 00:37:24.340
So you know, I think being
pragmatic is really critical.

00:37:24.340 --> 00:37:26.830
It gives us an
opportunity not to have

00:37:26.830 --> 00:37:29.880
to hire a helicopter,
which is much louder

00:37:29.880 --> 00:37:31.990
and noisier and intrusive.

00:37:31.990 --> 00:37:35.880
But like everything else,
drones have their place.

00:37:35.880 --> 00:37:38.630
And they have a lot of places
where they shouldn't be flying.

00:37:38.630 --> 00:37:40.835
And a lot of people that
don't know how to fly it

00:37:40.835 --> 00:37:41.710
should not be flying.

00:37:41.710 --> 00:37:45.640
So I think it's already at the
point where you need a license,

00:37:45.640 --> 00:37:46.940
and you need to be smart.

00:37:46.940 --> 00:37:50.860
The minute some yahoo from--
I forget where they were.

00:37:50.860 --> 00:37:54.730
I think they were French-- flew
it into the Grand Prismatic

00:37:54.730 --> 00:37:58.550
Spring in Yellowstone, the
entire National Park system

00:37:58.550 --> 00:38:00.720
banned them from the parks.

00:38:00.720 --> 00:38:02.730
So there you go.

00:38:02.730 --> 00:38:05.240
But I do love the technology
of seeing something

00:38:05.240 --> 00:38:08.280
from a different point of view.

00:38:08.280 --> 00:38:09.390
Yes?

00:38:09.390 --> 00:38:12.920
AUDIENCE: So what, if any,
postprocessing have you done

00:38:12.920 --> 00:38:14.170
or have you experimented with?

00:38:14.170 --> 00:38:15.836
And what did you think
about the stuff--

00:38:15.836 --> 00:38:21.480
ART WOLFE: So postprocessing
in the digital means making

00:38:21.480 --> 00:38:23.760
your image look
analogous to the film

00:38:23.760 --> 00:38:26.430
that you may have been
using prior to switching

00:38:26.430 --> 00:38:28.050
from film to digital.

00:38:28.050 --> 00:38:32.930
So what we do in Lightroom
is 25 points of vibrancy,

00:38:32.930 --> 00:38:35.860
five points of saturation,
a little bit of contrast.

00:38:35.860 --> 00:38:37.630
And bing, bang, boom,
you're basically

00:38:37.630 --> 00:38:41.960
like a piece of Velvia
film that we would use.

00:38:41.960 --> 00:38:44.408
That's pretty much
the extent of it.

00:38:47.960 --> 00:38:49.530
Yes?

00:38:49.530 --> 00:38:52.312
AUDIENCE: So how do you
balance the taking pictures

00:38:52.312 --> 00:38:53.270
and the postproduction?

00:38:56.810 --> 00:38:59.320
How much time do you
take culling your photos

00:38:59.320 --> 00:39:00.540
and then processing them?

00:39:00.540 --> 00:39:01.790
ART WOLFE: OK, great question.

00:39:01.790 --> 00:39:03.410
So at any given
day-- for instance,

00:39:03.410 --> 00:39:07.590
as I've just indicated, I
was in Africa two weeks ago.

00:39:07.590 --> 00:39:08.790
And that was a 10 day trip.

00:39:08.790 --> 00:39:12.070
Every day before I
go to bed, I would

00:39:12.070 --> 00:39:14.210
see everything I
shot during the day,

00:39:14.210 --> 00:39:17.190
and pull the favorites
into a collection,

00:39:17.190 --> 00:39:20.610
and more than likely work on
them until 1:00 in the morning

00:39:20.610 --> 00:39:21.510
before I go to bed.

00:39:21.510 --> 00:39:23.939
Because I know if I
didn't do it then,

00:39:23.939 --> 00:39:25.480
it's not going to
happen the next day

00:39:25.480 --> 00:39:27.246
because there's all
these new photos that

00:39:27.246 --> 00:39:28.120
are going to be shot.

00:39:28.120 --> 00:39:32.530
So I'm compulsive
on getting it done.

00:39:32.530 --> 00:39:35.590
Yesterday afternoon, I
was being driven back

00:39:35.590 --> 00:39:36.940
from the San Juan Islands.

00:39:36.940 --> 00:39:39.970
And I had the laptop on my lap.

00:39:39.970 --> 00:39:42.260
And I was working on the images.

00:39:42.260 --> 00:39:43.890
And I think they
got posted today.

00:39:43.890 --> 00:39:46.170
So I don't ever delay it.

00:39:46.170 --> 00:39:48.696
It's done right on
the day I shoot.

00:39:48.696 --> 00:39:50.480
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:39:50.480 --> 00:39:53.234
ART WOLFE: It helps
to be type A. Yeah?

00:39:53.234 --> 00:39:54.400
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:39:54.400 --> 00:39:57.210
So with the transition
from film to digital,

00:39:57.210 --> 00:40:00.730
is there anything you found that
you had to unlearn or relearn

00:40:00.730 --> 00:40:02.584
or do differently?

00:40:02.584 --> 00:40:04.000
ART WOLFE: It was
remarkable to me

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:06.750
because the people
in my office said--

00:40:06.750 --> 00:40:10.080
and I have a staff
that go back 26 years.

00:40:10.080 --> 00:40:13.320
Several of the women in my
office have gone back 26 years.

00:40:13.320 --> 00:40:18.974
And they told me when the 12
megapixel camera came out,

00:40:18.974 --> 00:40:20.390
you either buy one
or you're going

00:40:20.390 --> 00:40:21.764
to be a dinosaur,
because we were

00:40:21.764 --> 00:40:24.810
doing a lot of testimonials
for film and technology.

00:40:24.810 --> 00:40:27.880
So I got a digital camera.

00:40:27.880 --> 00:40:28.970
I got a computer.

00:40:28.970 --> 00:40:29.880
I got hard drives.

00:40:29.880 --> 00:40:33.780
I got all the things you
would need to shoot digitally.

00:40:33.780 --> 00:40:36.470
And then I went
off to Antarctica

00:40:36.470 --> 00:40:38.900
with 500 rolls of film
and my film camera.

00:40:38.900 --> 00:40:43.110
And on the route south across
the Drake Passage, I went out

00:40:43.110 --> 00:40:44.820
and I thought OK,
I've got to find out

00:40:44.820 --> 00:40:46.690
what the heck digital is about.

00:40:46.690 --> 00:40:49.350
So I took a pitcher
of water beating up

00:40:49.350 --> 00:40:52.870
and rain out on the
side of the boat.

00:40:52.870 --> 00:40:54.940
And five minutes
later I was uploading

00:40:54.940 --> 00:40:56.440
it to see if I can do that.

00:40:56.440 --> 00:40:58.550
And when I saw
the image come up,

00:40:58.550 --> 00:41:01.580
virtually I never have
taken a shot of film.

00:41:01.580 --> 00:41:03.670
So it was absolutely
like a meat cleaver.

00:41:03.670 --> 00:41:08.770
The switch from film-- and all
500 rolls of film came back.

00:41:08.770 --> 00:41:10.104
And I gave that film away.

00:41:10.104 --> 00:41:11.020
I didn't even sell it.

00:41:11.020 --> 00:41:12.060
I just gave it away.

00:41:12.060 --> 00:41:14.340
So it's all about the image.

00:41:14.340 --> 00:41:19.210
And that was when digital
was on par with film.

00:41:19.210 --> 00:41:23.070
Now it's outpaced it tenfold.

00:41:23.070 --> 00:41:25.710
And it keeps getting better
and better and better.

00:41:25.710 --> 00:41:28.950
I'm able to shoot
breaching orcas on Sunday

00:41:28.950 --> 00:41:31.120
afternoon that they
would have been

00:41:31.120 --> 00:41:32.720
all but impossible with film.

00:41:32.720 --> 00:41:33.970
So there's no regrets.

00:41:33.970 --> 00:41:34.970
There's no looking back.

00:41:34.970 --> 00:41:38.550
I can make the digital
capture look like any film

00:41:38.550 --> 00:41:39.560
that I preferred.

00:41:39.560 --> 00:41:42.890
So I know that many of my
colleagues struggled with that.

00:41:42.890 --> 00:41:44.300
They love their film.

00:41:44.300 --> 00:41:46.020
I'm not emotional about that.

00:41:46.020 --> 00:41:49.650
It was about the subject and
whether I could get it better.

00:41:49.650 --> 00:41:50.850
Thank you for that question.

00:41:53.650 --> 00:41:55.650
AUDIENCE: Pointers about
shooting in Antarctica?

00:41:55.650 --> 00:41:56.816
I'm going there in December.

00:41:56.816 --> 00:41:59.840
So any advice on
photography in Antarctica,

00:41:59.840 --> 00:42:01.342
I would much appreciate it.

00:42:01.342 --> 00:42:03.050
ART WOLFE: If you're
going to Antarctica,

00:42:03.050 --> 00:42:07.012
I think that if you bring--
what kind of camera do you use?

00:42:07.012 --> 00:42:08.160
AUDIENCE: A Nikon.

00:42:08.160 --> 00:42:09.300
ART WOLFE: Nikon.

00:42:09.300 --> 00:42:12.490
And with Canon, they
have a 100 to 400 zoom.

00:42:12.490 --> 00:42:17.160
Nikon undoubtedly has
something that equates to that.

00:42:17.160 --> 00:42:19.500
And if you don't own it,
then you could rent it.

00:42:19.500 --> 00:42:22.450
You don't have to go out
and buy expensive equipment

00:42:22.450 --> 00:42:24.439
for one trip.

00:42:24.439 --> 00:42:26.480
But that would be a great
one because really, you

00:42:26.480 --> 00:42:30.240
don't need much more than 400.

00:42:30.240 --> 00:42:32.645
You know, I use wide
angles and midranges.

00:42:32.645 --> 00:42:34.710
You know, the
penguins are close.

00:42:34.710 --> 00:42:36.290
The landscape's big.

00:42:36.290 --> 00:42:39.500
Unless it's an iceberg that
you can't get close to,

00:42:39.500 --> 00:42:42.500
there is no reason to
bring big glass down there.

00:42:42.500 --> 00:42:45.620
So 100 to 400 would
be really adequate.

00:42:45.620 --> 00:42:48.804
AUDIENCE: How do you deal with
the weight and the walking?

00:42:48.804 --> 00:42:49.720
So that's been a big--

00:42:49.720 --> 00:42:51.412
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:51.412 --> 00:42:52.870
ART WOLFE: There's
not much weight.

00:42:52.870 --> 00:42:55.680
AUDIENCE: 200 to
500, that's pretty--

00:42:55.680 --> 00:42:59.020
ART WOLFE: 100 to 400 is a lens
of about that big and about

00:42:59.020 --> 00:42:59.540
that.

00:42:59.540 --> 00:43:02.900
You can carry that,
one camera body.

00:43:02.900 --> 00:43:06.250
Even today you don't
really need a tripod.

00:43:06.250 --> 00:43:09.650
I mean, there are times where
I bring a tripod always,

00:43:09.650 --> 00:43:12.370
like the volcanoes
at night or stars.

00:43:12.370 --> 00:43:18.790
But for the most part, today--
I used to advocate tripods

00:43:18.790 --> 00:43:20.490
on everything.

00:43:20.490 --> 00:43:24.900
But today you really don't
know-- you know, frequently

00:43:24.900 --> 00:43:27.560
with the high end Canon
cameras that I use,

00:43:27.560 --> 00:43:31.630
I'm shooting at ISO 4,000.

00:43:31.630 --> 00:43:34.720
Noise is more of a
manifestation of length

00:43:34.720 --> 00:43:37.480
of shutter speed than ISO.

00:43:37.480 --> 00:43:43.040
And so I can shoot all day
long with ISO 4,000 or 2,000

00:43:43.040 --> 00:43:46.160
and tweak it a little
bit with noise reduction,

00:43:46.160 --> 00:43:47.890
and I'm good to go.

00:43:47.890 --> 00:43:48.390
Yes?

00:43:48.390 --> 00:43:50.046
AUDIENCE: Do you just need
a thick [INAUDIBLE] 4,000

00:43:50.046 --> 00:43:51.620
and just shoot,
shoot, shoot, or do

00:43:51.620 --> 00:43:55.350
you send it to an auto
ISO, 4,000 to the max?

00:43:55.350 --> 00:43:57.410
ART WOLFE: I don't use
auto ISO, although I have

00:43:57.410 --> 00:43:59.100
friends that just swear by it.

00:43:59.100 --> 00:44:02.840
When I'm shooting
a breaching whale,

00:44:02.840 --> 00:44:06.110
like I was on Sunday afternoon,
and I have no clue where

00:44:06.110 --> 00:44:09.870
they're going to come
up, in a 360 degree view,

00:44:09.870 --> 00:44:14.090
I put it at 4,000 so
I could shoot at f/22.

00:44:14.090 --> 00:44:16.120
And so I found that
I was just reacting.

00:44:16.120 --> 00:44:21.130
And if the whale was within
a fairly big radius, at f/22.

00:44:21.130 --> 00:44:22.310
It's going to be in focus.

00:44:22.310 --> 00:44:24.530
I don't have time to
even switch and try

00:44:24.530 --> 00:44:27.190
to focus because the whale's
gone, underwater again.

00:44:27.190 --> 00:44:33.420
So that's why those faster
ISOs really serve me.

00:44:33.420 --> 00:44:37.800
Right after the eclipse images
I shot, I was along a river.

00:44:37.800 --> 00:44:39.800
And I had-- and if you
look on our website,

00:44:39.800 --> 00:44:41.290
you'll see these photos.

00:44:41.290 --> 00:44:44.700
Giant hippos and crocodiles
were duking it out.

00:44:44.700 --> 00:44:48.260
So ISO 4,000 gave me depth
of field and shutter speed

00:44:48.260 --> 00:44:51.930
when they were happening.

00:44:51.930 --> 00:44:54.040
And I'm not really
compromising quality.

00:44:54.040 --> 00:44:56.110
I also have a 50
megapixel camera

00:44:56.110 --> 00:45:00.840
that I always shoot at ISO
100 for the big landscapes.

00:45:00.840 --> 00:45:04.770
But for action type
shots, 4,000 now

00:45:04.770 --> 00:45:08.570
is frequently what I'm using.

00:45:08.570 --> 00:45:12.210
I'm not a tech-- I really don't
like talking about technology,

00:45:12.210 --> 00:45:14.840
but it would be ridiculous
not doing it in this group.

00:45:20.648 --> 00:45:22.636
DAVID: You get the
honor of last question.

00:45:22.636 --> 00:45:24.760
ART WOLFE: You better make
this damn question good,

00:45:24.760 --> 00:45:27.330
because this is
the very last one.

00:45:27.330 --> 00:45:29.221
AUDIENCE: Well is
there any anyplace

00:45:29.221 --> 00:45:30.970
that you haven't been
that you want to go?

00:45:30.970 --> 00:45:32.880
ART WOLFE: Yeah, I
want to go to Socotra.

00:45:32.880 --> 00:45:37.450
Does anybody want to
go to Socotra with me?

00:45:37.450 --> 00:45:39.280
You want to go?

00:45:39.280 --> 00:45:40.300
AUDIENCE: Maybe

00:45:40.300 --> 00:45:43.320
ART WOLFE: It's an
island off Yemen.

00:45:43.320 --> 00:45:45.840
It's only accessed through
the capital of Yemen.

00:45:45.840 --> 00:45:48.340
It's halfway to Somalia.

00:45:48.340 --> 00:45:53.470
And they have the most bizarre
tree life on the planet.

00:45:53.470 --> 00:45:56.350
So that's why I
want to go there.

00:45:56.350 --> 00:45:57.710
And I've been waiting.

00:45:57.710 --> 00:45:59.310
I waited eight
years for the Congo

00:45:59.310 --> 00:46:01.080
to quiet down before I went in.

00:46:01.080 --> 00:46:04.070
I have no delusions
that I'm going to become

00:46:04.070 --> 00:46:06.210
a mercenary photographer.

00:46:06.210 --> 00:46:10.850
I waited until there was a peace
treaty signed in Goma, Congo

00:46:10.850 --> 00:46:12.820
before I went up
on that volcano.

00:46:12.820 --> 00:46:15.790
I think Sanaa, which is
the capital of Yemen,

00:46:15.790 --> 00:46:17.017
has quieted down.

00:46:17.017 --> 00:46:18.600
I just want to get
out to that island.

00:46:21.750 --> 00:46:23.070
I want to go to Oman.

00:46:23.070 --> 00:46:27.550
I want to go to Saudi
Arabia and that area.

00:46:27.550 --> 00:46:29.230
Israel I've not been to.

00:46:29.230 --> 00:46:31.450
So there's pockets
that I've not been to.

00:46:31.450 --> 00:46:33.960
I've not been to
Spain yet, though I

00:46:33.960 --> 00:46:36.310
have five books on Spain.

00:46:36.310 --> 00:46:37.490
So I know all about Spain.

00:46:37.490 --> 00:46:40.360
But I've relegated a lot
of the easier countries

00:46:40.360 --> 00:46:45.010
to places that I'll
go in my old age.

00:46:45.010 --> 00:46:46.600
So I just had a
birthday yesterday.

00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:48.120
I turned 65.

00:46:48.120 --> 00:46:52.260
And I'm ready to go
tomorrow morning.

00:46:52.260 --> 00:46:55.130
AUDIENCE: Have you ever
though about going to space?

00:46:55.130 --> 00:46:58.360
ART WOLFE: My staff has
really advocated that.

00:46:58.360 --> 00:47:00.120
Yeah, get on that rocket.

00:47:00.120 --> 00:47:00.620
No.

00:47:00.620 --> 00:47:04.640
You know, there was a-- I
would love to photograph

00:47:04.640 --> 00:47:06.400
the earth from orbit.

00:47:06.400 --> 00:47:07.880
There's no question.

00:47:07.880 --> 00:47:11.770
Any colleague of mine
would really like to do it.

00:47:11.770 --> 00:47:15.660
Unless you're a billionaire,
that's been unaccessible.

00:47:15.660 --> 00:47:18.765
Probably in my lifetime
it will be accessible.

00:47:18.765 --> 00:47:20.930
So I'd love to do that.

00:47:20.930 --> 00:47:22.270
OK David, thank you.

00:47:22.270 --> 00:47:23.260
DAVID: Thank you very
much for coming today.

00:47:23.260 --> 00:47:24.885
ART WOLFE: All right,
thanks everybody.

00:47:24.885 --> 00:47:25.650
[APPLAUSE]

00:47:25.650 --> 00:47:27.500
Thank you.

